 Farming-based Money flow 32 (2005) 181-193 
 
 Costs and benefits of animals systems and the role 
 of market and nonmarket relationships 
 Henk A. J. Moll a-- 
 Wageningen University, Wageningen, The Netherlands 
 Received 7 March 2002; received in changed form 3 March 2003; accepted 13 June 2003 
 
 Abstract 
 In developing countries animals are kept not only for their physical products, but also for insurance, financing, and to display 
 status. Though this range of purposes is admitted/recognized, animals policies anyway often focus on physical production: 
 a limited (way of seeing things / sensible view of what is and is not important) that slows the creation and (putting into) use of effective animals policies. This article presents 
 a complete evaluation of costs and benefits of animals systems that takes into account the institutional (surrounding conditions) of 
 animals keepers. Indicators are developed that (act of being taken or controlled by force), number, and organize not only the benefits resulting from the physical 
 production, but also those from the (can't be touched) functions. The method is illustrated by an analysis of (cows, bulls, etc.)  in the Western Area of control/area of land 
 of Zambia. The results point to/show that the opinion about  animals systems developed more closely reflects the watched/followed decisions 
 of the animals keepers. 
 JEL classification: O13; O22; Q18 
 Keywords: Markets; Nonmarket relationships; Animals; Policy analysis; Evaluation 
 
 1. Introduction 
 Millions of land-related families in developing countries keep animals as their main farming-based business/project or as an business/project linked to crop production. The 
 roles animals play in these families are (many different things): 
 the production of milk, meat, hides, poop/fertilizer, draught 
 power, etc. as well as the collection of wealth, security against (events that are dependent on other things that might or might not happen), and display of status. These 
 different roles are admitted/recognized, with animal scientists usually (focusing mental and physical effort) on physical production, and 
 social scientists also/and including parts of financing, insurance, and status display in their analysis 
 (Baker and Bhargava, 1974; Bosman and Moll, 1995; 
 a-- Tel.: +31-317-484354; fax: +31 317 484037. 
 E-mail address: Henk.Moll@wur.nl (H. A. J. Moll). 
 
 Doran et al., 1979; Low, 1986; Moll and Heerink, 1998; 
 Rosenzweig and Wolpin, 1993; Udo and Cornelissen, 
 1998). 
 Animals development policies, including research 
 policies, generally focus on the physical production 
 of animals systems, often with a focus on marketed production (Behnke, 1985), and in that way neglect 
 the many functions of animals. One of the ways 
 in which this restricted opinion about  production becomes seen/obvious is in the issue of the working well of 
 "traditional" animals systems, such as (cows, bulls, etc.)  grazed 
 on shared land or free-roaming goats. Policy analysts generally describe these systems as "low productive," because the off-take rate is well below potential 
 levels. Animals keepers, however, seem to be much 
 less concerned with working well in this narrow sense, 
 and are prepared to keep low productive animals in 
 
 182 
 
 H. A. J. Moll / Farming-based Money flow 32 (2005) 181-193 
 
 their groups. The (based on what's seen or what seems obvious) (different/branching out into different) opinions on 
 animals by policy analysts (and policy makers) and 
 by animals keepers slows the creation of effective animals policies that take into account both the 
 government's and animals keepers' viewpoints. 
 The difference in opinions on animals rises 
 mostly because policy analysts leave out/keep out the institutional (surrounding conditions) of animals keepers, whereas 
 animals keepers include it. In developing countries 
 this institutional (surrounding conditions) is seen as illfunctioning, (not there; not present), or nonaccessible markets for products, production factors, finance, and insurance. This 
 means that the values of useful things/valuable supplies used for and products came/coming from animals are not necessarily reflected 
 in market prices, and that animals reaches roles in insurance, financing, and display of status. The last thing just mentioned 
 was clearly (showed/shown or proved) by Bennison et al. (1997) 
 in a study of (cows, bulls, etc.)  keepers in The Gambia where the 
 first (or most important) production goal proved to be the generation of savings, security, and valuable thing protection. In this 
 situation the standard cost-benefit analysis has serious 
 faults/problems and the results rarely reflect the opinions of animals keepers. It should therefore come as 
 no surprise that animals keepers often use production methods that deviate from the "best" methods 
 pictured by policy analysts. 
 This article presents an evaluation of costs and benefits of animals systems that aims to make policy analysis and resulting animals policies more effective by 
 focusing on the total complex of market and nonmarket 
 relationships of the animals system within the wider 
 big picture  of the institutional (surrounding conditions) of animals 
 keepers. The approach is based on: (a) a difference between repeating production and clearly shown/included production 
 to deal separately with regular income streams and irregular income from the sale of animals; (b) a difference between marketed and nonmarketed useful things/valuable supplies and 
 production, which leads to a discussion of prices and 
 values for individual animals keepers; and (c) recognition and guess of the services animals provide in insurance, financing, and status display. The 
 approach is related to all types of animals, either 
 individually or in groups. In this the analysis moves away 
 from the approach followed by Crotty (1980) who developed separate models for different types of animals. 
 The approach builds on the discussion of measuring the 
 benefits of animals by Behnke (1985) and expands 
 the money-based analysis to include the results 
 
 of the institutional (surrounding conditions) of animals keepers. 
 The result is a combination of cash income, noncash 
 income, and (can't be touched) benefits instead of a money-making state as a single limit/guideline. The evaluation (completes/goes along with) biophysical animals and crop-animals models 
 (Devendra and Thomas, 2002a, 2002b; Thornton and 
 Herrero, 2001) that mostly focus on the relationships between animals and crop businesses/projects and their 
 physical (surrounding conditions) as these put into numbers biophysical 
 relationships form the starting point for the (putting a value on something) 
 and test of useful things/valuable supplies and products. 
 Section 2 deals with the method in four steps. In 
 Section 3 the approach is applied to (cows, bulls, etc.)  grazed on 
 natural (area of grassy land) in Western Area of control/area of land, Zambia. Ends/end results about the method are given in Section 4. 
 2. The method 
 The evaluation starts with the organization of the 
 put into numbers useful things/valuable supplies used for a animals system and 
 the physical production received/got. After that follows 
 the (putting a value on something) of useful things/valuable supplies and physical production 
 within the farm household system, taking into account 
 the presence or (not being there; not being present) of markets for useful things/valuable supplies and 
 production. The benefits came/coming from the functions of 
 animals in insurance, finance, and status display are 
 discussed in the third stage, and in the final evaluation 
 the total benefits of the animals system are related 
 to the household's production factors used, by that/in that way 
 taking into account their options and preferences. The 
 analysis is shown in Fig. 1. 
 The focus of the analysis is on the animals system, 
 but this animals system is part of the farm household 
 system that may contain crop and care systems, as 
 well as other on-farm and off-farm businesses/projects. The 
 possible relationships between animals and crop systems are included in this analysis. The position of the 
 animals system vis-`a-vis other on-farm and off-farm 
 businesses/projects will be briefly organized and listed at the end of this 
 section. 
 2.1. Useful things/valuable supplies and production 
 Biophysical input-output data of the animals system form the starting point of the analysis. These data 
 are usually once-a-year averages per group in a steadystate situation, or averages per type of animal over 
 
 H. A. J. Moll / Farming-based Money flow 32 (2005) 181-193 
 
