 or given away. The clearly shown/included production per period 
 is usually measured by subtracting the clearly shown/included production at the end of period t a' 1 from the clearly shown/included 
 production at the end of period t. 
 2.2. Prices and values of useful things/valuable supplies and production 
 
 Fig. 1. The animals system in the wider big picture. 
 
 its lifetime. The input-output data are this way the (connecting point/way of interacting with something) between, on the one hand, the complex biophysical processes that deal with reproduction, growth, and 
 death, and on the other hand the (putting a value on something) of inputs 
 used and outputs received/got that result in an ex post test of the benefits of the system (Bosman et al., 
 1997). 
 In this method, the useful things/valuable supplies used in animals production are split into repeating (bought something for money) inputs and 
 the household's production factors directly employed, 
 such as family labor, land, and capital invested in animals and stables. Examples of repeating (bought something for money) 
 inputs are medicines and drugs, feed adds to/helpful additions and 
 food, hand tools, hired labor, and veterinary services. 
 The reason for this honor/difference lies in the (putting a value on something) of 
 the useful things/valuable supplies, which is dealt with in the next sections. 
 Animals production is separated into repeating production and clearly shown/included production. Repeating production becomes available according to the animals's 
 type, sex, age, and the season. Examples are products 
 and services such as milk, wool, poop/fertilizer, and draught 
 power. Clearly shown/included production refers to changes in body 
 weight, pregnancy (as proof of life-creating ability), and change in 
 abilities through training, or to changes in numbers 
 of animals if the analysis is at herd level. Clearly shown/included 
 production is this way production that is not ate/destroyed 
 but that is kept in animals as an investment. This investment results in future repeating production or it 
 becomes available when animals are murdered, sold, 
 
 To test the (thing that's given/work that's done) of animals to the income 
 of the animals keeper the useful things/valuable supplies used and production received/got must be valued. This (putting a value on something) is not a 
 plain/honest/easy process, as markets for useful things/valuable supplies and 
 products are (not totally pure/not totally correct) or even except for and this way do not 
 provide prices. More than that, animals keepers may have 
 differential access to markets, which means that the 
 price received/got by farmer x may differ from the price 
 received/got by farmer y, while for farmer z, who has no 
 access to that market, neither price is (connected/related). 
 Some of the useful things/valuable supplies and products are valued 
 through markets where supply and demand conditions result in prices. The nonmarketed useful things/valuable supplies and 
 products are valued within the families, using as 
 a yardstick the combination of useful things/valuable supplies, options for 
 using these useful things/valuable supplies, and preferences (designed only for/happening only within)  that 
 household. 
 For the analysis of the repeating production, the difference between marketed and nonmarketed outputs, 
 the former with market prices and the last thing just mentioned with guessed prices (both at farm gate level), is maintained in 
 the following two indicators. 
