 The gross margin is the complete indicator for the 
 value of the net on-farm physical production of the animals system received/got by using the families' production factors. Combining the three parts/pieces into 
 one indicator helps the analysis, but for animals 
 keepers this one indicator is not (capable of being seen and known). However, 
 as the parts/pieces each are (capable of being seen and known) we may assume 
 that farm families take them all into account in their 
 test of animals systems. 
 The (putting a value on something) of the household's production factors 
 labor, land, and capital directly employed in the system 
 is discussed in the final analysis in Section 2.4. 
 
 2.3. The functions of animals in insurance, 
 financing, and status display 
 The functions of animals as security against (events that are dependent on other things that might or might not happen), as a means of financing, and in the display 
 of status are significant in communities where it is hard  or impossible to satisfy these functions by other 
 means. The (not being there; not being present) or (bad or poorly)-functioning of markets for 
 finance and insurance in developing countries, especially in areas away from cities, has been widely recorded/supported by, 
 for example, Von Pischke et al. (1983), Binswanger 
 and Rosenzweig (1986), Adams and Fitchett (1992), 
 Bosman and Moll (1995), and Hoogeveen (2000). The 
 result of the (not being there; not being present) or restricted presence of 
 finance and insurance institutions is that to deal with 
 the changes of life, people in areas away from cities search for other choices within their world/area/ball of command. Among the 
 possibilities are keeping animals, collecting gold and 
 jewelry, and investing in tree crops. 
 The insurance function of animals results from the 
 (possible power or ability within/possibility of)  being able to sell the animals in case of 
 emergencies. Having animals is this way similar with 
 having insurance, and the (not being there; not being present) of the need to pay 
 a higher cost can be thought about/believed the average (can't be touched) 
 benefit. Sieff (1999) carefully studied the relationship between 
 wealth and animals patterns of the (made something unimportant) 
 Datoga (people who raise many sheep, cattle, etc.) in Tanzania and showed that the 
 poorest families were forced to sell more animals 
 than were replaced by reproduction, and so were 
 faced with lessening groups. This reflects an extreme 
 situation: the families are not only too poor to keep 
 low productive animals as insurance, but they are also 
 forced to sell their productive animals. The insurance 
 function is important not only as it wasations where no 
 other means of storing wealth are available, but even 
 when there are other insurance options, because animals are easily convertible valuable things. 
 Insurance payments provide cover to a specified 
 limit for a serious and stubborn period, and the benefit of insurance, Bst , is therefore related to the average value of 
 animals for period t: 
 Bts = bs (Pta'1 + Pt )/2, 
 
 (5) 
 
 where bs is a factor pointing to/showing a proportion of the average sale value. To guess the factor bs , the different 
 insurance options must be tested. In their analysis of 
 dwarf goats in Southern Nigeria, Bosman et al. (1997) 
 
 H. A. J. Moll / Farming-based Money flow 32 (2005) 181-193 
 
 used an informal life insurance system described by 
 Ibe (1992), with a once-a-year higher cost of around 0.10 as 
 reference. Ayalew (2000) has discussed informal group 
 insurance in the Ethiopian highlands and guessed the 
 insurance benefit of goats to be 0.083 of the average 
 value of the stock. If other choice options are not present 
 a (guessed number that's probably close to correct) is needed/demanded, and a range from 0.05 for stable situations without major weather risks to a factor of 
 0.20 for situations with extreme risks, seems reasonable. 
 The function of animals in financing is (able to be seen/worthy of attention) 
 in three things: the (instance of buying something for money) of animals when 
 income goes beyond consumption needed things (Dercon 
 and Krishnan [1996] discuss income (mixes of stocks, bonds, etc./document collections) in (away from cities) 
 Ethiopia and Tanzania); the investment of clearly shown/included 
 production; and, the sale of animals mostly for 
 immediate consumption or investment needed things. 
 The last thing just mentioned thing/event is recognized in different facts or conditions (that surround someone). Behnke (1985) states in a discussion on 
 the price of camels, "richer Desert-living Arab continued to sell 
 a limited number of animals in order to meet their perceived very important rice needed things"; Low (1986) created the "sale for clearly stated/particular cash needs" guess in 
 the big picture  of (cows, bulls, etc.)  marketing in Swaziland; and Moll 
 and Dietvorst (1999) found in the Western Area of control/area of land of 
 Zambia that animals keepers just sold (cows, bulls, etc.)  in case of 
 a big and important needed thing of cash. Selling 
 animals to meet specified needed things has a number 
 of advantages: 
 - hedge against inflation, as the real value of animals 
 generally remains fairly stable; 
 - there is no need to keep cash safe (this is hard  in 
 (away from cities) facts or conditions (that surround someone)); 
 - the presence of cash is avoided, by that/in that way avoiding 
 possible claims from others that are hard to refuse 
 for social reasons; 
 - avoidance of storage losses if animals are swapped/switched 
 for goods; 
 - avoidance of the cost involved in borrowing for eating/drinking or investment purposes. 
 The benefit of financing through animals this way results 
 from the avoidance of cost involved either in storing 
 money or products (that are bought and sold), or in borrowing. However, the sale of 
 animals when there is a need, and not at the best 
 moment as figured out by/decided by the physical production or 
 prices, hints a trade-off between the benefit from 
 financing and the maximal cash returns. 
 
 185 
 
 The measurement of the function in financing must 
 focus on the sale (or direct consumption) of animals 
 because this forms a clearly (able to be seen or picked out) event, and because measuring the outflow covers previous investment behavior through the collection of clearly shown/included 
 production and the (instance of buying something for money) of animals. The benefit of 
 financing, B f , is related to the sale price: 
 f 
 
 Bt = bfPt , 
 
 (6) 
 
 where b f is a proportion of the sale price. The factor 
 b f can be guessed by (thinking about/when one thinks about) the cost or loss 
 got/caused in different ways of financing, such as: having a savings account; storing grain; getting informal credit; or, pawning jewelry or (able to last through tough conditions) person 
 products (that are bought and sold). In the studies by Bosman et al. (1997) and 
 Ayalew (2000) the guesses are based on the avoidance 
 of inflation for Nigeria, and on commercial interest 
 rates for short- and medium-term credit for Ethiopia, 
 (match up each pair of items in order), resulting in values for b f of 0.06 and 0.10. 
 The function of animals in providing status to their 
 owners is related to the presence or (not being there; not being present) of other 
 means to display wealth, such as (able to last through tough conditions) person 
 products (that are bought and sold)  and building materials. Status may not be an 
 completely (can't be touched) benefit, as it may play a role in owning influence, and (after that) increasing access 
 to useful things/valuable supplies. The benefit from providing status is, as 
 in insurance, related to the average value of an animal 
 (or animals) over period t: 
 p 
 
 Bt = bp (Pta'1 + Pt )/2, 
 
 (7) 
 
 where b p is a proportion of the average value. For an 
 guess of factor b p a value below the value for insurance seems appropriate as insurance, which may mean 
 survival, generally has a higher priority than status. 
 At best, guessing the factors bs , b f , and b p deciding/figuring out the benefits in insurance, financing, and status 
 display is guided by other choices that change/differ  in relevance. 
 Actual guesses this way require (not definite) judgments, 
 and so are open to debate. Yet as it wasations where markets are (not there; not present) or (bad or poorly)-functioning, doubtful guesses 
 are (certain to happen). 
 2.4. The analysis 
 The total benefit came/coming from animals production 
 is composed of the gross margin plus the benefits from 
 
