 (9) 
 
 the sale price plus the benefit of financing. One could 
 argue that the total benefit of selling an animal is reflected in the sale price. The sale price, however, does 
 not play a important role in the decision to sell when 
 markets are partially (not there; not present): it is not the sale price that 
 triggers the sale of an animal, but the purpose for which 
 the sale price received is needed/demanded. The benefit of selling an animal, Bst , this way reflects the benefit of having 
 the sale price in hand at the right time. 
 The expression of the benefits of a single animal into 
 two indicators similar things the difference between "production value" and "liquidity value" used by Baker 
 and Bhargava (1974) in their explanation on liquidity management, but in our analysis both terms have a wider 
 definition. 
 The total benefit of keeping an animal during n years, 
