 The addition of all income parts/pieces into one limit/guideline BÂ¯ should not hide the trade-off among the 
 parts/pieces. This trade-off comes from/is caused by both biophysical and (how money affects people's lives) factors. For example, keeping 
 low-productive animals in the group on a limited area 
 reduces overall (related to the body function of living things) working well, but increases 
 the benefits from insurance and status. 
 The total benefit, either for a single animal or for 
 a group, results from the use of the household's 
 production factors--labor, land, and capital (L, G, and 
 C, (match up each pair of items in order)). Giving-out the total benefit over the 
 production factors to decide/figure out the (pertaining to each person or thing) returns 
 needs/demands prices for the production factors: 
 BÂ¯ = (L Ã-- pl ) + (G Ã-- pg ) + (C Ã-- pc ), 
 
 (12) 
 
 with p l , p g , and p c the prices for labor, land, and capital, 
 (match up each pair of items in order). These prices are either (partly) (not there; not present), or 
 not (connected/related) for all animals keepers, and this prevents 
 a general statement on the returns per production factor. However, the formula shows that, given the total 
 benefit and the amounts of labor, land, and capital used, 
 there is a trade-off among the returns per production 
 factor. 
 Animals keepers will test the animals system in 
 terms of the types of income came/coming from keeping and 
 selling on the one hand, and the household's production factors used on the other hand (Staal, 2000), and 
 will do so remembering their possibilities for using 
 their production factors in other on-farm and off-farm 
 businesses/projects; see Fig. 2. 
 The result of this test may differ by 
 household according to their particular goals and 
 values for the different income parts/pieces, their 
 factor gifts, and their access to institutions. 
 Analysts lack these individual and (not definite) references, but the complete evaluation of costs and 
 benefits presented above offers a (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) for combining guesses with watched/followed data. Sensitivity analysis of the guesses allows the analyst to relate the 
 total benefit of a animals system to a range of facts or conditions (that surround someone) experienced by different groups of animals 
 keepers. 
 
