 Fig. 2. Evaluation of the animals system. 
 
 3. An test of (cows, bulls, etc.)  in Western 
 Area of control/area of land, Zambia 
 The method is illustrated by applying it to (cows, bulls, etc.)  production in the Western Area of control/area of land of Zambia. 
 (cows, bulls, etc.)  are kept in combination with crop production 
 and this combination is (existing all over a large area) in Southern Africa. 
 The data on the physical production were collected 
 through herd watching over a period of 5 years 
 (Brouwer et al., 1992; Corten, 1988; van Klink, 1990). 
 Prices and values were collected and guessed during 
 an overall test of the crop and animals subsectors (Mwafulirwa and Moll, 1991). The analysis below 
 refers to an average individual animal, a cow, over a 
 lifetime of 15 years, the lifetime covered in the herd 
 watching. 
 About 30% of the families in the Western Area of control/area of land keep (cows, bulls, etc.). The animals, of the Barotse 
 type, are kept in groups of 30 to 100 head, owned by 
 some people. During the daytime the animals 
 graze on natural (area of grassy land), under the control of a herdsman. At night they are kept in enclosures, kraals, that 
 are shifted often to spread the poop/fertilizer over the 
 fields where maize and millet will be grown. Meat production is the main purpose of the system, but cows are 
 milked (leaving enough milk for the calf), and little bulls 
 are used for transport and ploughing. 
 3.1. Useful things/valuable supplies and production for one cow 
 Labor is used for moving, shifting kraals, and 
 for milking. The capital included in the animals is 
 big: it forms 90% of the total valuable things of the 
 cattle-keeping families (Moll and Dietvorst, 1999). 
 
 (almost nothing/very little) amounts of working capital are used to buy 
 medicines. There is enough scope for more (cows, bulls, etc.)  in 
 the Western Area of control/area of land, so land (natural (area of grassy land)), is not 
 very hard to find and access is free. The useful things/valuable supplies used and the 
 production received/got over the lifetime of a cow are 
 shown in Table 1. On average the (related to the process of making children) period 
 of the cow starts in year 4, with some cows giving birth 
 in year 3 and a larger proportion as late as in year 5; 
 this distribution is reflected in the table. The average 
 number of calves per cow is about 3.5, with an 
 average calving period of time (or space) of 1.6 years. The weight gain 
 becomes close to zero from year 7 onward. 
 3.2. Prices, values, and indicators 
 The prices refer to the average prices during 1990. 
 The price for milk in the (related to a local area) capital, Mongu, was 
 10 K/liter, but in areas away from cities the price was (in a big way) 
 lower, so an average price of 5 K/liter has been used 
 to value the milk. 1 Most of the milk is ate/destroyed by 
 the household or swapped/switched in the community, but an 
 guessed 25% of the milk is sold for cash. (bought something for money) 
 inputs refer to veterinary drugs and medicines sold by 
 the Western Area of control/area of land Cooperative Union. There is no 
 market for poop/fertilizer, so the value of poop/fertilizer has been guessed as the total price of an amount of (material that makes plants grow better) with 
 equal nutrient parts/pieces. This is a (probably a little low) 
 guess, as crops on the sandy soils benefit from the 
 organic matter also. In a more commercially oriented situation in Kenya, Lekasi et al. (1998) found 
 that the market value of poop/fertilizer was about five times 
 1 Kwacha, the currency unit in Zambia; the average rate of exchange in 1990 was K 29 = US$1. 
 
