 the value of the equal (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.) in (material that makes plants grow better). Productive cows are usually not sold, as a (cows, bulls, etc.)  keeper 
 will exchange such a cow for an ox from another (cows, bulls, etc.) 
 keeper if cash is needed/demanded. As a result, no prices were 
 available for cows in the (related to the process of making children) phase, and in 
 this analysis the price of a cow is based on the farm 
 gate price of 14 K/kg live weight paid for murder 
 animals by iterant traders (Table 2). The net repeating 
 cash income from a milked cow is small, around 150 K 
 (US$5) every year. The repeating income in kind during 
 the productive period was equal to 31 kg of maize 
 in year 3, 118 kg in year 5, and to 17 kg from year 
 11 onward. The once-a-year added value reached 1,063 K 
 in year 5 and after that got less to close to 75 K 
 (US$2.6). 
 3.3. Benefits in insurance, financing, 
 and status display 
 The Zambezi floodplain, where most of the (cows, bulls, etc.) 
 in Western Area of control/area of land are kept, is (only a little bit) good 
 for crop production. In average-to-good years the production of maize and millet might just be (good) enough 
 to meet the household's consumption needed things, 
 
 but in years with below average rainfall, staple food 
 must be (bought). In these facts or conditions (that surround someone) (cows, bulls, etc.)  form 
 the major insurance against hunger, as there is no formal insurance. A factor of 0.05 to 0.10 would reflect 
 a range of (compared to other things) good to bad/unhelpful local 
 facts or conditions (that surround someone). 
 Most of the (cows, bulls, etc.)  keepers had no access to (money-related) 
 institutions, and even if they had had access to one of 
 the two banks in the (related to a local area) capital Mongu, a savings account would have been unattractive as interest 
 rates on savings were negative in real terms due to inflation. In way of thinking/basic truth/rule, it is possible to store wealth in the 
 form of maize, but rodents and pests take a heavy toll. 
 In these facts or conditions (that surround someone) the most attractive option in financing is to keep animals until a big amount of 
 cash is needed/demanded (Moll and Dietvorst, 1999). A benefit 
 factor of 0.10 has been taken to reflect the unattractive 
 potential other choice modes of financing. 
 (cows, bulls, etc.)  offer a major opportunity to express status 
 in the (away from cities) communities, and people are known for 
 the size of their group. A benefit factor of 0.03 has 
 been taken to value the status aspect. The benefits in 
 insurance, financing, and status display are shown in 
 Table 3. 
 
