 The including in something in the analysis of these (can't be touched) 
 benefits has results for the decision to sell an 
 animal as it affects both the benefit from selling an 
 animal and the net present value of future production 
 (Fig. 3). The lines a, b, and c represent the net present 
 values of future production from the years pointed to/showed 
 until the end of year 15, including the sale of the 
 animal at the end of year 15. A discount rate of 0.10 
 represents the time preference. Because this analysis 
 
 is based on average production data, death is not 
 included. Including in something would not change the analysis as 
 the trash value does not move away (in a big way) from 
 the live weight value in the Western Area of control/area of land. Line a 
 shows a situation in which the benefits in insurance 
 and status display are not (connected/related) (bs and b p are both 
 0.00). Line b represents the present value of total future 
 benefits in a low-risk situation with benefit factors for 
 insurance and status display of 0.05 and 0.03 (match up each pair of items in order). A higher risk situation is shown by line c with 
 a benefit factor for insurance of 0.10. The lines d and 
 e show the total benefit of selling an animal during 
 the year, with benefit factors for financing of 0.00 and 
 0.10, (match up each pair of items in order). Lines d and a show a possible 
 situation with fully functioning markets for insurance, 
 financing, and status display (benefit factors all 0.00). 
