 Fig. 3. Comparison of the sale value of a cow with the present value (PV) of keeping a cow, taking into account benefits for insurance, financing, 
 and status display. 
 
 year 6, as the sale price (line d) rises above the present 
 value of future production (line a). The combination 
 of line e with lines b and c reflects the situation in the 
 Western Area of control/area of land. The combination of lines e and b 
 represents low-risk situation, and the combination of 
 line e with line c represents the high-risk situation with 
 sales around year 12. The three combinations show 
 that with increasing importance of insurance, the moment of sale moves/changes toward the end of the lifetime of the 
 animal. 
 Cows older than 11 years account for only 2% of 
 the female animals in the Western Area of control/area of land and this 
 points to/shows that lines e and c reflect the view of 
 (cows, bulls, etc.)  keepers in an extreme situation, with high risk 
 leading to big benefits of (cows, bulls, etc.)  in insurance. 
 Fig. 3 shows that the overall effect of the including in something 
 of the benefits for insurance, financing, and status is 
 that the value of keeping animals increases relative to 
 the value of selling animals. This finding is in line 
 with the discussion by Low (1986) on the reasons for 
 keeping and selling (cows, bulls, etc.)  in the big picture  of nonmarket 
 benefits of (cows, bulls, etc.)  ownership in Southern Africa. It also 
 shows the limits of herd (testing out) models that 
 just focus on the interaction between herd size, herd 
 composition, and (something you choose to do, but is not required) dispatch. 
 This analysis of (cows, bulls, etc.)  at herd level in the Western 
 Area of control/area of land would show the existence of groups with older 
 animals than would be expected on the basis of an best physical production. In other situations, where 
 total food availability is the limiting factor, these 
 
 older animals fight against animals in the most important part of 
 physical production, the result being a total physical 
 production below what is possibly possible from 
 the available food useful things/valuable supplies. Zemmelink (1995) did 
 research in such a situation in East Java and compared 
 total feed useful things/valuable supplies with the total group of (buffaloes, deer, antelopes, etc.). 
 He found that the total group was (in a big way) larger 
 than the best size for physical production, and 
 decided that this could only be explained by taking 
 into account the benefits from the insurance function. 
 In East Java, and under the same conditions, there 
 is this way a trade-off between the benefits from physical production and the benefits from insurance, and 
 status. 
 
 4. Discussion and ends/end results 
 The method to carefully study animals systems described 
 and (showed/shown or proved) above first enables some income indicators to be created that (act of being taken or controlled by force), number, 
 and organize the different benefits of a animals system. 
 Some of the income indicators are based on current 
 market prices and are mostly valid for all animals 
 keepers. However, the indicators "income in kind" and 
 the (can't be touched) benefits are related to household (features/ qualities/ traits) that may differ (in a big way), such as household (combination of different substances, objects, people, etc.) and access to banks. 
 The identification of separate income indicators, that 
 together take by force/take control of total income, this way allows a focus on 
 
 192 
 
 H. A. J. Moll / Farming-based Money flow 32 (2005) 181-193 
 
 different groups of animals keepers. Second, for the 
 overall evaluation of the animals system, the summary of the different income indicators is related to the 
 costs of the system in terms of the household's production factors employed, by that/in that way taking into account opportunity costs. Again, animals keepers usually differ 
 in factor gifts and the evaluation can change something (to help someone)/take care of someone the different options open to different groups. 
 The relative importance of the indicators will differ 
 with the animals systems under analysis and the presence or (not being there; not being present) of markets for useful things/valuable supplies, production, 
 and services. The (cows, bulls, etc.)  production carefully studied in Section 3 happened in a situation with almost (not there; not present) markets for useful things/valuable supplies and services, a simple market 
 for milk, and with a functioning market for murder 
 animals. The case reflects an extreme, but not unusual/amazing, situation of restricted access to markets. In more 
 market-oriented systems, such as dairy production near 
 city-based  areas, the importance of the net repeating cash 
 income will be more well-known/obvious and more visible. However, the linkages with crop production (repeating income in kind) and the benefits in financing and insurance may still add/give (in a big way) to the total 
 benefit of the system. Also, in more marketoriented animals systems the household's production 
 factors--labor, land and possibly also capital--usually 
 have other choice opportunities in farming-based and 
 nonagricultural businesses/projects that generally have clearly 
 (able to be seen or picked out) types of income. The use of the 
 complete evaluation of costs and benefits of animals systems is therefore gave a reason for in a wide range of 
 facts or conditions (that surround someone). 
 Including the markets for useful things/valuable supplies, production, and services in the analysis of animals systems 
 enables (people who work to find information) and policy makers to test these 
 systems more closely from the viewpoint of the animals keepers. This is highly (connected/related) for the development of effective animals policies, because animals 
 keepers will test all proposed changes in the production system in the big picture  of their goals, factor 
 gift, and institutional (surrounding conditions). 
 
